{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930102801/0285.xml":{"full_text":"SMITH PLEDGES\nSHORTER WEEK\nTOR WORKERS\n\nPROVIDENCE, R. 1., Oct. 28\n(LNJS.). \u2014A shorter work week\nand \"real government economy\u201d\nwore promised America by former\nGovernor Alfred E. Smith, of New\nYork, providing electors \u201cvote the\nDemocratic ticket.\u201d\nSpeaking here last night Gov\nernor Smith attacked President\nHoover's policies and said the\nRepublicans had promised pros\nperity when they knew they\n\u201ccould not deliver.\u201d He said:\n\u201cWhen there are hard times\nin the Republican party they\narc usually referred to as a\n*business depression,\u2019 but in a\nDemocratic administration they\nare called panics.\u201d\nWhile the Democrats \u201chad too\nmuch sense to accuse any politi\ncal party of responsibility for\nbusiness depression\u201d the former\ngovernor said the Republicans had\nmade false promises apd deceived\nthe electors. He said that only\nin the last few days through the\nappointment of Col. Arthur Woods\nto take the leadership in the\nfifht to relieve unemployment\nhad the National Administration\ntaken any cognizance of the seri\nousness of the situation.\nThe former executive will speak\nin Boston tonight.\nNeighborhood, House\nTo Hear Music Club\nIf embers of the Neighborhood\nHouse, 470 N St. S. W., will be\nentertained tonight by the Tues\nday Evening Music Club, with a\nprogram arranged by the Kiwanis\nClub.\nSolos will be sung by Ina\nHoltzscheiter, Catherine Gross,\nCecile Littlefield and Helen Neu\nmyer Perry, while other members\nto contribute selections are Lillian\nLeweUyn, Reba Hill. Helen Wil\nliams, Gladys Wilcox. Frances\nTucker, Laura Lyle, Grace Brown,\nMarjorie Brocket t, Virginia\nCooper, Mary Pauli, Adelaide Har\nbers, Clara Forbes, Enid Williams,\nand Donna Taggert, accompanist.\nMrs. Frank P. Howard will direct.\nBeauty Industry\nLacks Text Book\nChicago, oct. 28 (lnjs.).\nWanted: A text book on beauty.\nWhen State authorities suggest\ned that beauty culture schools\nadopt standard reference books\non subjects upon which can\ndidates for State licenses must\nbe examined, it developed that no\none knew of any.\nNearly all beauty culture books\nnow used are written by manu\nfacturers.\nRead the BUSINESS SERVICE I\u00bbI\n--RECTORY of today\u2019* Clattftlfied Ad*.\nIt will direct yoo to dependable home\nar office eerrlcee.\n1 Waterman\u2019s IH fill 1\n9 Lady Patricia i IH II 'A I\nW jj| :\u2018fl\nf|| p: mm s\u00a3?!\u25a0\u25a0\nfl There's a beautiful new pen at your I Waterman's ink \u2014tbt ink that\u2019s mad*\n9 Waterman\u2019s dealer now Water* 1 IjlHP'f' J or fountain ppns Wtterman\u2019s new\n9 man\u2019s Lady Patricia. In three smart II Blue Ink for general correspondence\n9 costume colors\u2014 Persian, glowing f 11 and school use,Waterman\u2019s Blue-Black fl\nIS Mce a black opah Jet, contrasted ot record purposes. Then ask to f\nwith chromium trim; and Onyx, a IBH see Waterman\u2019s finest man\u2019s pen\u2014the L\ncream-and-tawny combination. De* Patrician. Your choice of fire jewel\n9 signed by women for women\u2014and v colon and seven pen points Pen, $10;\n9 completely feminine from cap to E| I pencil, $5. A wonderful gift, when\n'll pen point. When you try this you want the best. Other Waterman's\nI new pen be sure to have it filled with I in great variety of models and prices.\nA SMART CLASP REPLACES THE MASCULINE CLIP 1\nHOLDS IT SECURELY IN PLACE IN YOUR HANDBAG I\nSEVEN TYPES OF PEN POINTS TO- CHOOSE FROM H\nONE OF WHICH FITS YOUR HANDWRITING EXACTLY\nfi v f if'\nGRACEFULLY SHAPED TO FIT FEMININE FINGERS\nYET HOLDING PLENTY OF INK 7 I\nFIVE DOLLARS FOR THE PEN, THREE FOR THE PENCIL\nOR BOTH, IN A BEAUTIFUL GIFT BOX, EIGHT DOLLARS\nBeery Waterman's is guaranteed forever against de> L. E. ViWtttM Company\nfecta. Service Stations are maintained >t die addreae- 191 Broadway, New York 40 School St, BoMoa\ntt below for the purpose of making good oar 129 So. State St, Chicago 609 Market Street, San\nowe and for Krvicrog our prat u required. uire.l, C.un\nThief Freed, That 9 s If\nHe Goes to Church\nFor a Year\nSTAUNTON, Va.. Oct. 28.\nFor a year at least, Frank\nSipes must go to church.\nArraigned before Justice E.\nA. Aldhizer, at New Hope, in\nthis county, charged with steal\ning two automobile tires, tubes\nand a rim from J. F. Small, the\nyoung man was required to\nmake restitution for the prop\nerty he is alleged to have taken\nand to bear court costs.\nHis Honor was willing to let\nit go at that provided Frank\nposted a peace bond to insure\nhis regular attendance at church\neach Sunday during the ensu\ning year. His mother is his\nsurety.\nFrank may go to any church\nhe chooses \u2014just so he goes.\npfflTloyp\nLAUDS HEARST\nWiHiam Randolph Hearst was\npraised for the he has\nconducted for adequate national\ndefense at a meeting last night\nof the National Patriotic Coun\ncil. in its Navy Day observance.\nMrs. Cornelia Ross Potts, presi\ndent of the council, urged the\nnecessity of preparedness and\nlauded Mr. Hearst, as did Col.\nJ. Edward Cassidy, president of\nthe United States \u00a3ir Force As\nsociation: Lieut. C S. Perry, U.\nS. N., and Rexford L. Holmes,\nsecretary of the council.\nSecretary Holmes said:\n\u201cI want to take this oppor\ntunity to voice my warm ad\nmiration of the patriotic work\ndone by William Randolph\nHearst in campaigning for an\nadequate national defense.\n\u201cHe deserves the support of\nthis council and other patriotic\norganisations in his campaign\nto secure a Navy for the United\nStates which will be able to\nprotect our shores and our com\nmerce. He has never failed to\nlend sympathetic attention to\nthe needs of our Navy and has\nfought against pll attempts to\ncripple it and make it inferior\nto the navies -of foreign\npowers.\u201d\nMrs. Potts said she had found\nthe attitude of the Hearst news\npapers most helpful in the cause\nof preparedness and patriotism.\nA membership drive was voted,\nwith Miss Helen Norris Cum\nmings, of Virginia, as chairman\nof the membership committee.\nSeveral other committee chairmen\nwere named. Col. Joseph M.\nHeller, national secretary of the\nMilitary Order of the Carabao,\nmade a brief speech.\nU.S. RUBBER GETS MAREAN\nF. B. Davis, jr., president U. S.\nRubber Co., has announced that\nB. E. Marean, first vice presi\ndent, Electric Hose Rubber Co.,\nof Wilmington, will join the U.\nS. organization on November 1.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nFIRE DESTROTS\nCLUBHOUSE\nFALLS CHURCH, Va, Oct. 28.\nA fire of unknown origin starting\nearly today destroyed the old\nclubhouse on the golf course\nknown as the Campbell course,\njust west of this town.\nFour fire companies, from Falls\nChurch, Fairfax, Vienna and\nCherrydale, were called out to\nfight the fire, but they could\nmake little progress against the\nflames because of the lack of\nwater for fire-fighting purposes.\nThe clubhouse, which stands in\nback of the Chimney Villa, a\nroadhouse, which was in danger\nseveral times from sparks, was\noccupied by W. Frazer, who was\nliving there as a tenant and care\ntaker. Mr. Frazer had planned to\nmove out today.\n[CHEVY CHASE DAIRY\nTruly \u201cSomething to Crow\nAbout!\u201d-\u2014just as fresh as can\nbe, just as white-shelled as can\nbe, and every egg of a size and\nweight which must equal or ex\nceed two ounces each.\nDozen and Half-Dozen Car\ntons. We know you will enjoy\nthese Eggs if you but try them.\nLet us deliver a carton tomorrow\nmorning.\n\"Wise Brothers\nVJIp CHEW CHASE\nijSSi DAIRY\n3206 N St N.W.\u2014WEST 0183\nHagerstown Citizen\nWorks Daily at 88\nHAGERSTOWN, Md., Oct. 21.\nWilliam T. Grove, who just cele\nbrated the eighty-eighth anniver\nsary of his birth works every day\nat the Hagerstown Mantle and\nFurniture Works,- and has no\nthought of retirement.\nAsked the secret of his lon\ngevity and present good health,\nhe generally replies with a\ntwinkle in his eye that he was em\nployed for six years in the Rox\nbury distillery in this county, but\nhe hastens to assure everybody\nthat he has yet to taste moonshine\nliquor.\ni GUARANTEED of\u00df\n1 KAY'S J\n409-7 Street N-W-\nThm National Dail*\nM| 11111 n w llii\nSUCAR GUNDERSHIMER\u2019S RICH LAYER\n10 47\u00ab JEL 2*-65\u00ae\nTRE .HIP E I OCEAN SPRAY I GOLD BAG\nnr a rurc cranberry\nF\u00a3iAtH\u00a3S sauce COFFEE\n2 Can. 35C No. >W 19\u00a9 33 Lb. 29\u00ab\nLibby\u2019s c<|mpfire MLKINS COFEEE lb. 35c\nFruit For Salad Marshmallows ORIENTA COFFEE lb. 39c\n_ No. 1 Tall can 22c _ Quaker Oats pkg. lie\nForest King Peas can 15c 164 z. Pkg. 21C Cream of Wheat\nClicquot Club lg pkg# 24c\nGinger Ale 2 bottle. 276 PREMIER Sweet P\u00ab\u201e\u00bbke\n4 botl.. (contents) 25c DKESSIRO VERMONT MAID SYRUP\n3 lge.botls. (contents) 25c 12C &*33 C SSk\u2122\u2122\"'\" 12 OZ. Jug 23c\nSTAR SPECIALS\nSchimmel's p\u00abr. Preserves 32-oz. Jar 37c\nLibby's Bartlett Pears 2 No. 1 Tall Cans 29c\nPillsbury\u2019s Best Flour\nin All Your Baking -49 c\nCamay Soap 4 Cakes 25\u00ab\nHtHJSE Pure Apple Cider i-Gal. Pitcher 33\u00ab\nAnglo Cooked Corned Beef it\u00bb 23c\ntill I I\nCAMPBELL'S II fg? C S?Jm TA ALDERNEY\nBEANS M 2Sc 1 sie milk\nI WASHINGTON Yc w _\n-C FLOUR fc&ari Qt. 13c\nJ Cans AjC I, 2 Lbs 24 Lk 89c I Sold at AU Our Stores\nAyrshire Butter Rich in Quality Pound 51e\nGold Band Butter \"\u201cb zxr* Pound 47c\nBee Brand Pure Extracts 2 Mies 25c\nRitter Catsup 8-oz. Bottle 10c 14-oz. Bottle 15c\nBrewer-Snyder Cooked Hominy Qt. Container 12c\nN. Auth\u2019s pure pork Sausage Meat Pound 35c\nChlpso PLAIN or granules Urge Pkg. 22c\nGold Dust 2 Small Pkgs. 9c Large Pkg. 23c\nFly-TOX FOR INSECTS Small Bottle 39C Large Bottle \u00a39C\nf FRESH FRUITS AND VEGETABLES j) TOC pUlt V lO\u00ae\nFANCY JUICY I APPf PC Th. Original\nFlorida All Pork Sausage\nOranges 4 lbs C PBIMd 4^ c\n_ _ Fancy FOUNTAIN BRAND\nDoZs 49c Jonathan 3 Lb, 20* 11 HAMS\n1 _ n 7 Pound\nFancy California Carrots 2 Bunches 15c\